mediaNotes: This recording contains the "Peek," "Sputter," and "Wicka-wicka" calls described in the BNA account. These calls might have been given in response to my presence, but there was also a forest raptor (likely Buteo platypterus or B. linearis) in the area, so the calls might have been in response to the raptor's presence. This pair had a nest with nestlings in the immediate vicinity of this recording. One of the two individuals in this recording is also the subject of LNS 163345. Other Behaviors: Emit Alarm. Habitat: Deciduous Forest.
Drumming on telephone pole
Continuous begging calls are heard from the juvenile in the nest cavity along with periodic calls from the male who was foraging near the nest and feeding the juvenile.
The bird was recording while partially emerged from the nest cavity.
Tapping can be heard between calls. I used a play back to get the bird to come closer so I could try for a photo and a sound recording.

Drumming of unseen woodpecker that flew off after last drum recorded--before I could get to within sight. It was coming from pine-oak woodland along Rucker Creek at the uppermost Rucker Campground, 1700m. Hairy, Acorn, & Arizona woodpeckers and N. Flickers were all seen in the general area. It's too fast for Acorn drums, and it sounds to me most like that of a Hairy. Recorded on a clear, chilly morn (49F at dawn, warming once the sun got over the mountains), using a Fostex FR-2LE with a Sennheiser ME62 & Telinga Universal parabola.
mostly rattles and hard peek notes; also some very brief handling noise
